<v HOST_2>You're absolutely right, Sarah. Because for all its incredible speed and efficiency, AI-generated code comes with some very serious risks. It's truly a double-edged keyboard.

119
00:19:21.393 --> 00:19:23.601
<v HOST_1>What kind of risks are we talking about?

120
00:19:23.901 --> 00:19:35.589
<v HOST_2>Let's not mince words: security. Studies have found that AI-generated code has been shown to contain two point seven four times more vulnerabilities than code written by humans.

121
00:19:35.889 --> 00:19:42.465
<v HOST_1>Two point seven four times more? That's not just a little bit more, that's significantly more!

122
00:19:42.765 --> 00:20:01.893
<v HOST_2>Exactly. And we're not talking about minor bugs. Approximately forty-five percent of AI-generated code samples introduced what's known as O-WASP Top Ten vulnerabilities. These are the most critical, common security flaws. Cross-site scripting, for example, had an eighty-six percent failure rate.

123
00:20:02.193 --> 00:20:08.649
<v HOST_1>So AI code is basically a security nightmare waiting to happen, if left unchecked.

124
00:20:08.949 --> 00:20:24.837
<v HOST_2>Potentially, yes. And it gets worse. There's a forty percent increase in secrets exposure. Things like hardcoded A-P-I keys and passwords, just left out in the open. Imagine your bank account details, or your company's secret sauce, exposed because the AI didn't know better.

125
00:20:25.137 --> 00:20:29.720
<v HOST_1>Wow. So it might be fast, but it's not smart about security.

126
00:20:30.020 --> 00:20:38.876
<v HOST_2>Not in the way a human is, no. You know, Linus Torvalds, the creator of the Linux kernel, famously called large language models bullshit generators.

127
00:20:39.176 --> 00:20:42.320
<v HOST_1>Bullshit generators? That's direct.

128
00:20:42.620 --> 00:20:57.428
<v HOST_2>He said they don't understand anything and don't know anything, just producing smooth-sounding output, any part of which could be bullshit. And that's the core of the problem: AI can confidently generate code that looks correct, but is fundamentally flawed or insecure.

129
00:20:57.728 --> 00:21:02.984
<v HOST_1>Do you have an example of that disconnect? Where it just... doesn't get it?

130
00:21:03.284 --> 00:21:14.492
<v HOST_2>Oh, I have a horror story for you. Imagine an Apprentice Chef. You ask this apprentice to make a simple dish. They quickly whip it up, but they've used expired ingredients and left out crucial safety steps.

131
